/F1 11 Tf
1 0 0 1 50 742 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 728 Tm (## 3. Evaluation: Measuring the Wrong Unit) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 714 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 700 Tm (The first symptom of the unit problem is evaluative. In long-horizon, tool-using, budget-) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 686 Tm (constrained workflows, observed outcomes depend on more than the model. They depend on) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 672 Tm (workflow structure, environment, and budget. Yet benchmark discourse often presents results) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 658 Tm (as if they were clean model comparisons.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 644 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 630 Tm (This creates a mismatch between the **measured unit** and the **discussed unit**. A) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 616 Tm (benchmark may in practice test a workflow-conditioned system while being reported as) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 602 Tm (evidence about the model alone. The result is not that benchmarks become useless, but that) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 588 Tm (their causal interpretation becomes unstable.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 574 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 560 Tm (Two systems built on the same model may differ substantially in recoverability,) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 546 Tm (auditability, cost efficiency, or success rate because workflow structure differs.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 532 Tm (Conversely, two different models may converge in practical quality because scaffolding and) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 518 Tm (budget compensate. When that happens, evaluation language that treats "the model" as the) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 504 Tm (central unit compresses away the structure that users and operators actually depend on.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 490 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 476 Tm (This is where the cascade begins. If evaluation reports are already built around a model) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 462 Tm (placeholder, then downstream explanation will inherit the same compression almost) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 448 Tm (automatically.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 434 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 420 Tm (## 4. Attribution: Explaining the Wrong Unit) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 406 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 392 Tm (The second symptom is explanatory. Even when a system-level behavior is correctly observed,) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 378 Tm (discourse often attributes it to the model by default.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 364 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 350 Tm (A system with external persistence becomes "a model with memory." A scaffold with retries) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 336 Tm (and checkpoints becomes "a robust model." A strong tool wrapper becomes "a model that can) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 322 Tm (use tools well." A continuity architecture becomes "an agent that stays itself.") Tj
1 0 0 1 50 308 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 294 Tm (These phrases are often convenient shorthand. But when workflow, harness, environment, or) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 280 Tm (budget substitution can materially alter the property while the model remains fixed, model-) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 266 Tm (centered attribution becomes unstable.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 252 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 238 Tm (The attribution problem is therefore different from the evaluation problem, though related) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 224 Tm (to it. Evaluation asks what is being measured. Attribution asks where an observed property) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 210 Tm (properly belongs once it has been observed. The unit problem reappears because the) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 196 Tm (explanatory bearer is frequently larger than the model.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 182 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 168 Tm (Here the cascade deepens. Once system-level outcomes are attributed to the model, the field) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 154 Tm (is encouraged to seek remedies, improvements, and narratives at the model layer first-even) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 140 Tm (when that is not where the relevant leverage or structure lives.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 126 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 112 Tm (## 5. Control: Seeking Leverage in the Wrong Place) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 98 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 84 Tm (The third symptom concerns intervention. If a system is difficult to stop, easy to redirect,) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 70 Tm (bounded, recoverable, or permissive, where does the practical leverage over that behavior) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 56 Tm (actually live?) Tj
ET
endstream
