BT
/F1 11 Tf
1 0 0 1 50 742 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 728 Tm (In many agent systems, it does not live mainly in the model. It lives in permissions,) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 714 Tm (workflow structure, checkpoint logic, external memory, budget ceilings, tool wrappers, and) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 700 Tm (human approvals. A system can become more stoppable, more reviewable, or less dangerous) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 686 Tm (without any change to the model at all.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 672 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 658 Tm (The unit problem appears here as a confusion between **explanatory ownership** and) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 644 Tm (**intervention target**. Even if the model contributes to the behavior, it may not be the) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 630 Tm (best place to act on it. If discourse keeps pointing to the model as the natural site of) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 616 Tm (control, it will miss the real intervention surfaces.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 602 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 588 Tm (This mislocation has downstream institutional consequences. Once the wrong intervention) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 574 Tm (target is assumed, governance frameworks will tend to inherit the same distorted picture of) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 560 Tm (where power and responsibility live.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 546 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 532 Tm (## 6. Governance: Governing the Wrong Object) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 518 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 504 Tm (The fourth symptom is institutional. Governance asks not only where leverage exists, but how) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 490 Tm (authority, review rights, accountability, contestability, and auditability are arranged.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 476 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 462 Tm (Here too, model-centered thinking breaks down. The acting object is not merely the model. It) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 448 Tm (is the larger action system composed of model, tools, persistence, permissions,) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 434 Tm (infrastructure, orchestration, and oversight relations. If governance continues to attach) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 420 Tm (mainly to the model, then oversight will be aimed at an important component while still) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 406 Tm (under-describing the actual system that acts in the world.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 392 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 378 Tm (This matters for regulation, procurement, audit, deployer responsibility, vendor power, and) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 364 Tm (public accountability. Claims like "the system is supervised" or "the model is safe" can) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 350 Tm (become structurally incomplete when the real governed object is larger than the model label) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 336 Tm (suggests.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 322 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 308 Tm (The cascade reaches its institutional endpoint here. Model-centered evaluation encourages) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 294 Tm (model-centered attribution. Model-centered attribution encourages model-centered control) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 280 Tm (thinking. Model-centered control thinking distorts governance. What began as a technical) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 266 Tm (simplification hardens into a political and organizational mistake.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 252 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 238 Tm (## 7. The Unit Problem as a Cascading Error) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 224 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 210 Tm (The unifying force of this synthesis is not merely that the four papers sit beside one) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 196 Tm (another. It is that they describe a causal chain.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 182 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 168 Tm (1. **Compression in evaluation** hides system structure behind model scores.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 154 Tm (2. **Compression in attribution** assigns system properties to the model by default.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 140 Tm (3. **Compression in control** looks for leverage at the model layer first.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 126 Tm (4. **Compression in governance** treats the model as the primary object of oversight even) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 112 Tm (when authority and action are distributed elsewhere.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 98 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 84 Tm (These are not four unrelated confusions. They are linked consequences of allowing one) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 70 Tm (placeholder object to occupy too many roles.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 56 Tm () Tj
ET
endstream
endobj
